The paper deals with combinatorial optimization problems on graphs, such as computing the Domatic Number and Chromatic Number, which are typically studied in the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) and Combinatorics (cs.CC) sub-categories. The use of Moebius inversion and set families suggests a connection to the Discrete Structures (cs.DS) sub-category. The focus on graphs of bounded degree and the use of an intersection theorem suggest a connection to the Graph Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. Finally, the use of polynomial time algorithms suggests a connection to the Computational Complexity (cs.CO) sub-category.
